# Step 3: This is the most important command

Run:

```bash
for j in BOOT-INF/lib/*.jar
do
  jar tf "$j" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "com/fasterxml/jackson/annotation/JsonFormat.class"
  if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
      echo "FOUND IN: $j"
  fi
done
```

This will tell us if any vendor jar is carrying its own Jackson classes.

---

# Step 4: Check the actual version inside `jackson-annotations`

```bash
jar xf BOOT-INF/lib/jackson-annotations-*.jar
javap -classpath . com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonFormat\$Feature | grep READ_UNKNOWN
```

If everything is correct, you should see:

```java
READ_UNKNOWN_ENUM_VALUES_USING_DEFAULT_VALUE
```

If you don't see it, then despite the filename being `2.17.2`, the jar itself is corrupted or not actually 2.17.2.

